\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
6.1.38
\end_layout

\end_inset

Find the determinant of the 
\begin_inset Formula $5\times5$
\end_inset

 matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
3 & 0 & 4 & 5 & 6\\
2 & 1 & 2 & 3 & 4\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 6 & 5\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 5 & 6
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\shape italic
Suggestion:
 Use row-reduction and Theorem 6.1.4,
 which says that the determinant of a triangular matrix is the product of its diagonal entries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
To find the determinant by row reduction,
 we row-reduce while keeping track of the multiplier term for operations that change the determinant:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\begin{array}{c}
\\R_{2}-3R_{1}\\
R_{2}-2R_{1}\\
\\\\\end{array} & \begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
3 & 0 & 4 & 5 & 6\\
2 & 1 & 2 & 3 & 4\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 6 & 5\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 5 & 6
\end{bmatrix} & (1)\\
\text{swap \ensuremath{R_{2}} and \ensuremath{R_{3}}} & \begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
0 & -6 & -5 & -7 & -9\\
0 & -3 & -4 & -5 & -6\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 6 & 5\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 5 & 6
\end{bmatrix} & (1)\\
\begin{array}{c}
\\\\R_{3}-2R_{2}\\
\\R_{5}-\frac{5}{6}R_{4}
\end{array} & \begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
0 & -3 & -4 & -5 & -6\\
0 & -6 & -5 & -7 & -9\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 6 & 5\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 5 & 6
\end{bmatrix} & (-1)\\
 & \begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3 & 4 & 5\\
0 & -3 & -4 & -5 & -6\\
0 & 0 & 3 & 3 & 3\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 6 & 5\\
0 & 0 & 0 & 0 & \frac{11}{6}
\end{bmatrix} & (-1)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

By the end,
 we have a triangular matrix,
 whose determinant is 
\begin_inset Formula $1\times(-3)\times3\times6\times\frac{11}{6}=-99$
\end_inset

,
 and accounting for the multiplicative term incurred by swapping two rows,
 we get:
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=99.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

