\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
6.2.42,
 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 be any 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix.
 We wish to show that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A^{\transpose}A)\geq0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

label=(
\backslash
alph*)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Explain what is wrong with the following attempt at a proof:
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(AB)=\det A\det B$
\end_inset

,
 we may write 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A^{\transpose}A)=\det(A^{\transpose})\det(A)$
\end_inset

.
 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A^{\transpose}=\det A$
\end_inset

,
 we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A^{\transpose})\det A=(\det A)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A^{\transpose}A)=(\det A)^{2}$
\end_inset

,
 and the square of a real number is always nonnegative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Here is a sketch of a proof that actually works.
 First,
 you will need the QR decomposition theorem (5.2.2),
 which allows us to write any matrix as a product 
\begin_inset Formula $A=QR$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is a 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{\transpose}Q=I$
\end_inset

,
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times m$
\end_inset

 matrix that is upper triangular (that is,
 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{ij}=0$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $i>j$
\end_inset

) and all of its diagonal elements are nonnegative.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

label=(
\backslash
roman*)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Write out the determinant 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A^{\transpose}A)$
\end_inset

 in terms of the diagonal entries 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{ii}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Conclude that this expression must be a nonnegative number.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Solution
(a) The issue is that,
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is not a square matrix,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A^{\transpose})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A)$
\end_inset

 are not well-defined,
 so the expressions in the middle of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

proof
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 make no sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
(b) Writing 
\begin_inset Formula $A=QR$
\end_inset

 as in the QR decomposition theorem,
 we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(A^{\transpose}A)=\det(R^{\transpose}Q^{\transpose}QR)=\det(R^{\transpose}R)=(\det(R))^{2},
\]

\end_inset

where the last equality is by the argument in part (a),
 which this time actually works because 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is a square matrix.
 This already shows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det(A^{\transpose}A)\geq0$
\end_inset

,
 proving (ii),
 but we were asked to write this determinant in terms of the diagonal entries of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

,
 so we will do that now.
 The determinant of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

,
 as an upper triangular matrix,
 is the product of its diagonal elements,
 i.e.
\begin_inset space \space{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\det R=r_{11}\dots r_{nn}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\det(A^{\transpose}A)=(\det R)^{2}=r_{11}^{2}\dots r_{nn}^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

This concludes the solution of (i),
 and with it the exercise.
\end_layout

