\begin_layout Exercise*
\begin_inset Argument 1
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
7.3.14,
 
\begin_inset Formula $*$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Diagonalize the matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\begin{bmatrix}6 & 3\\
2 & 7
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise*
This means:
 Write 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 as a product of three 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $ADB$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 is a diagonal matrix and 
\begin_inset Formula $AB=I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
First,
 we find the eigenvalues by using the characteristic polynomial.
 The characteristic polynomial is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(t)=\det\begin{bmatrix}6-t & 3\\
2 & 7-t
\end{bmatrix}=(6-t)(7-t)-3\cdot2=t^{2}-13t+36.
\]

\end_inset

The roots of this polynomial are 
\begin_inset Formula $t=4$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t=9$
\end_inset

.
 Thus,
 these are the eigenvalues.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
To find the eigenvectors,
 we find nonzero solutions to the equations 
\begin_inset Formula $(C-4I)\vec{x}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(C-9I)\vec{x}=0$
\end_inset

.
 We do this by row-reduction of the matrices in question.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $C-4I$
\end_inset

,
 we get the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
2x_{1}+3x_{2}=0,\\
2x_{1}+3x_{2}=0,
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

which has for example the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},x_{2})=(3,-2)$
\end_inset

.
 So this is our eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
For 
\begin_inset Formula $C-9I$
\end_inset

,
 we get the equation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
-3x_{1}+3x_{2}=0,\\
2x_{1}-2x_{2}=0,
\end{array}\right.
\]

\end_inset

which has for example the solution 
\begin_inset Formula $(x_{1},x_{2})=(1,1)$
\end_inset

.
 So this is our eigenvector 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Solution
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathfrak{B}=\{\vec{v}_{1},\vec{v}_{2}\}$
\end_inset

 be the basis of eigenvectors we obtained.
 In this basis,
 the transformation given by 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 looks like
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
[C]_{\mathfrak{B}}=\begin{bmatrix}4 & 0\\
0 & 9
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

We can then apply the change of basis formula.
 For this,
 we need to know the change of basis matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and its inverse.
 The matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\begin{bmatrix}3 & 1\\
-2 & 1
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Its inverse may be calculated by the adjoint formula:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{-1}=\frac{1}{5}\begin{bmatrix}1 & -1\\
2 & 3
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Thus,
 by the change of basis formula 
\begin_inset Formula $C=S[C]_{\mathfrak{B}}S^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
 we may write
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
C=\begin{bmatrix}6 & 3\\
2 & 7
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}3 & 1\\
-2 & 1
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}4 & 0\\
0 & 9
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\frac{1}{5} & -\frac{1}{5}\\
\frac{2}{5} & \frac{3}{5}
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

which is the decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $ADB$
\end_inset

 we wanted,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $A=S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B=S^{-1}$
\end_inset

 (hence 
\begin_inset Formula $AB=I$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

